/647164/c/34976/s/27e05c0b/a2.img" border="0"></a><img width="1" height="1" src="http://pi.feedsportal.com/r/151884887293/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27e05c0b/a2t.img" border="0"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/gizmodo/full/~4/mOg2joy7Eus" height="1" width="1">";s:9:"feed_link";s:19:"http://gizmodo.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:7:"Gizmodo";}s:32:"3e3a4b6d07cc94bfb8258ba3094da3bf";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:69:"In Germany, internet service providers pay you! (for loss of service)";s:4:"link";s:101:"http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/24/in-germany-internet-service-providers-pay-you-for-loss-of-service/";s:6:"author";s:12:"Joseph Volpe";s:4:"date";i:1359085440;s:7:"content";s:1995:"<p> <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/24/in-germany-internet-service-providers-pay-you-for-loss-of-service/"><img alt="German" data-src-height="428" data-src-width="600" src="http://www.blogcdn.com/www.engadget.com/media/2013/01/5-22-2011internet-switch-must-be-on.jpg"></a></p><p> Ever lost your internet connection? Do the loathsome words "executive customer service" resonate with you? They shouldn't if you live in <a href="http://www.engadget.com/tag/Germany/">Deutschland</a> -- at least, not after today. While that course of customer service whinging can <em>occasionally</em> yield some form of restitution stateside (we're being generous), for Germans it's now almost unnecessary. In a ruling issued today, a federal court in Karlsruhe has determined interruption of internet service to be grounds for compensation, as it can be categorized as an "essential material item," <em>Reuters</em> reports. The decision, which allows impacted users to file compensatory claims, stems from a 2008 - 2009 incident in which a private German citizen incurred a loss of phone, fax and internet service over a two month period. Apparently, the man had already been partially reimbursed for having to rely on mobile phone service, but decided to take things a little further. In other news, Americans can just threaten to switch to <a href="http://www.engadget.com/tag/verizonfios/">FiOS</a>. Worked for us.</p><p>Filed under: <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/internet/" rel="tag">Internet</a></p><p><strong><a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/24/in-germany-internet-service-providers-pay-you-for-loss-of-service/#comments">Comments</a></strong></p><p><strong>Source:</strong> <a href="http://www.reuters.com/article/2013/01/24/us-germany-internet-idUSBRE90N15H20130124?feedType=RSS&amp;feedName=technologyNews&amp;utm_source=feedburner&amp;utm_medium=feed&amp;utm_campaign=Feed%3A+reuters%2FtechnologyNews+%28Reuters+Technology+News%29" target="_blank">Reuters</a><!--//--></p>";s:9:"feed_link";s:24:"http://www.engadget.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:8:"Engadget";}s:32:"8b19ed0069295060786f69083aad2e04";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:53:"Seth MacFarlane Goes 'Psycho' in Oscars Promo (Video)";s:4:"link";s:66:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/thr/news/~3/JWiMn7ittY8/story01.htm";s:6:"author";s:11:"Aaron Couch";s:4:"date";i:1359084471;s:7:"content";s:2571:"<img src="http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/sites/default/files/2013/01/seth_macfarlane_oscar_promo_2_-_h_2013.jpg"><br>The Academy Awards host visits Bates Motel to promote the Feb. 24 ceremony.<p><a href="http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/seth-macfarlane-goes-psycho-oscars-415300" target="_blank">read more</a></p><img width="1" height="1" src="http://rss.feedsportal.com/c/34793/f/641578/s/27e05ab1/mf.gif" border="0"><div><table border="0"><tr><td valign="middle"><a href="http://share.feedsportal.com/viral/sendEmail.cfm?lang=en&amp;title=Seth+MacFarlane+Goes+%27Psycho%27+in+Oscars+Promo+%28Video%29&amp;link=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.hollywoodreporter.com%2Flive-feed%2Fseth-macfarlane-goes-psycho-oscars-415300" target="_blank"><img src="http://res3.feedsportal.com/images/emailthis2.gif" border="0"></a></td><td valign="middle"><a href="http://res.feedsportal.com/viral/bookmark.cfm?title=Seth+MacFarlane+Goes+%27Psycho%27+in+Oscars+Promo+%28Video%29&am