</div><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/thr/news/~4/JWiMn7ittY8" height="1" width="1">";s:9:"feed_link";s:33:"http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:18:"Hollywood Reporter";}s:32:"34d2f12f426a62e765f6078d53a28e0e";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:71:"Huawei Ascend P2 product shot leaked, confirms 13MP camera in slim body";s:4:"link";s:57:"http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/24/huawei-ascend-p2-leak/";s:6:"author";s:12:"Zachary Lutz";s:4:"date";i:1359084360;s:7:"content";s:2434:"<p> <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/24/huawei-ascend-p2-leak/"><img alt="Huawei Ascend P2 leaks with homegrown quadcore CPU and 45inch, 1080p display" data-src-height="450" data-src-width="619" src="http://www.blogcdn.com/www.engadget.com/media/2013/01/ascend-p2.jpg"></a></p><p> If the 170g Huawei <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/07/huawei-officially-announces-ascend-d2/">Ascend D2</a> is a bit too imposing for your hands, then you may be curious to know of the Ascend P2, a <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/10/huawei-8-core-chip-mwc-p-series/">previously teased</a> smartphone that was just leaked by @evleaks. While there's no further info to go along with this image, it does show off a 13MP camera on the back of the phone, which makes us wonder how Huawei even managed to pack that into the sub-6.45mm-thick metallic body. A little digging around also showed that the company's Consumer BG CEO <a href="http://engadget.com/tag/richardyu">Richard Yu</a> was seen fondling the P2 during a meeting back in December -- you can recognize the phone in the photo after the break. Naturally, we look forward to this successor to the <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2012/06/01/huawei-ascend-p1-review/">Ascend P1</a> at Mobile World Congress next month.</p><p> <em>Richard Lai contributed to this report.</em></p><p> <img alt="Huawei Ascend P2 product shot leaked, " data-src-height="413" data-src-width="620" src="http://www.blogcdn.com/www.engadget.com/media/2013/01/richard-yu-ascend-p2.jpg"></p><p> <img alt="Huawei Ascend P2 product shot leaked, " data-src-height="353" data-src-width="620" src="http://www.blogcdn.com/www.engadget.com/media/2013/01/richard-yu-drunk.jpg"></p><p>Filed under: <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/cellphones/" rel="tag">Cellphones</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/mobile/" rel="tag">Mobile</a></p><p><strong><a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/24/huawei-ascend-p2-leak/#comments">Comments</a></strong></p><p><strong>Source:</strong> <a target="_blank" href="http://www.unwiredview.com/2013/01/24/huawei-ascend-p2-first-press-shot-of-the-1080p-flagship/">Unwired View</a><!--//-->, <a target="_blank" href="http://bbs.huaweidevice.com/index.php?app=forum&amp;mod=Detail&amp;act=index&amp;id=110481&amp;auther=1&amp;pid=1507339">Huawei BBS</a><!--//-->, <a target="_blank" href="http://www.weibo.com/2334964577/zeiVQkNlf">Sina Weibo</a><!--//--></p>";s:9:"feed_link";s:24:"http://www.engadget.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:8:"Engadget";}s:32:"48b332c2f58e3f1f9bd34d89fbb2a5b3";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:65:"PBS profiles Martin Goetz, recipient of the first software patent";s:4:"link";s:99:"http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/24/pbs-profiles-martin-goetz-recipient-of-the-first-software-paten/";s:6:"author";s:15:"Donald Melanson";s:4:"date";i:1359083340;s:7:"content";s:1752:"<p> <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/24/pbs-profiles-martin-goetz-recipient-of-the-first-software-paten/"><img alt="PBS profiles Martin Goetz, recipient of the first software patent" data-src-height="342" data-src-width="620" src="http://www.blogcdn.com/www.engadget.com/media/2013/01/pbs-software-patents.jpg"></a></p><p> PBS has been exploring a fair bit technology history with its digital shorts lately -- examining the likes of <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2012/03/08/pbs-traces-the-history-of-animated-gifs-deal-with-it/">animated GIFs</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2012/10/05/pbs-mini-documentary-explores-indie-game-creation/">indie games</a> and <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/06/pbs-short-creative-coding/">coding as art</a> in its <em>Off Book</em> series -- and it's now tackled one issue that's making more headlines than ever: software patents. It hasn't provided a distilled history of the topic this time, though, instead offering a brief profile of the man who received the first software patent in 1968, Martin Goetz, as part of its <em>Inventors</em> series. Not surprisingly, he still sees a place for software patents, but admits that the current situation is "<span>a little bit of a mess." Head on past the break for the video.</span></p><p> </p><p>Filed under: <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/misc/" rel="tag">Misc</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/alt/" rel="tag">Alt</a></p><p><strong><a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/24/pbs-profiles-martin-goetz-recipient-of-the-first-software-paten/#comments">Comments</a></strong></p><p><strong>Source:</strong> <a target="_blank" href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yKdqJGgpcgg">PBS Inventors Series (YouTube)</a><!--//--></p>";s:9:"feed_link";s:24:"http://www.engadget.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:8:"Engadget";}s:32:"591058b0e72ad58684239e2380ab7573";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:42:"The Nutrition Facts of Food in Video Games";s:4:"link";s:97:"http://feeds.gawker.com/~r/gizmodo/full/~3/JiLkOrJuzRU/the-nutrition-facts-of-food-in-video-games";s:6:"author";s:10:"Casey Chan";s:4:"date";i:1359082800;s:7:"content";s:1940:"<div> <!-- div style="background-color: #B3B3B3; width: 190px; padding: 1px;"><a title="Click here to read The Nutrition Facts of Food in Video Games" href="http://gizmodo.com/video-games/" style="background-color:#888888; color:#FFFFFF; font-size:12px;text-align:right; display:block; height:14px; padding:1px 2px; text-decoration:none; text-transform:uppercase; width:156px;"><span style="color: white;" class="hash">#</span><span style="color: white;">videogames</span></a></div --> <div><a title="Click here to read The Nutrition Facts of Food in Video Games" href="http://gizmodo.com/5978881/the-nutrition-facts-of-food-in-video-games"> <img height="360" width="640" title="Click here to read The Nutrition Facts of Food in Video Games" alt="Click here to read The Nutrition Facts of Food in Video Games" src="http://img.gawkerassets.com/img/18cjgj7w8nuxbjpg/xlarge.jpg"></a></div> </div> We totally think that <a href="http://gizmodo.com/5978321/you-know-you-want-to-bring-delicious-video-game-food-to-life">bringing video game food into real</a> life would be an awesome idea. But what are the nutrition facts of those mushrooms that Mario eats or those glowing dots that feed Pacman? We need to know these things! <a href="http://gizmodo.com/5978881/the-nutrition-facts-of-food-in-video-games" title="Click here to read more about The Nutrition Facts of Food in Video Games">More&nbsp;&raquo;</a> <br><img width="1" height="1" src="http://gizmodo.feedsportal.com/c/34976/f/647164/s/27e053a0/mf.gif" border="0"><br><br><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/151884886050/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27e053a0/a2.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/151884886050/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27e053a0/a2.img" border="0"></a><img width="1" height="1" src="http://pi.feedsportal.com/r/151884886050/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27e053a0/a2t.img" border="0"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/gizmodo/full/~4/JiLkOrJuzRU" height="1" width="1">";s:9:"feed_link";s:19:"http://gizmodo.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:7:"Gizmodo";}s:32:"533c27a9403484edcdcdf28f4c9efb72";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:56:"'Grey's Anatomy' Postmortem: Can Seattle Grace Be Saved?";s:4:"link";s:66:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/thr/news/~3/XF7kCAAf7sk/story01.htm";s:6:"author";s:15:"Lesley Goldberg";s:4:"date";i:1359082800;s:7:"content";s:2662:"<img src="http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/sites/default/files/2013/01/greys_anatomy_walking_on_a_dream.jpg"><br>Patrick Dempsey, Sara Ramirez, Sarah Drew, James Pickens Jr., Chandra Wilson and Constance Zimmer talk with T