TV commercial and print campaign, directed by Edouard SALIER.";s:9:"feed_link";s:23:"http://www.behance.net/";s:10:"feed_title";s:25:"Behance Featured Projects";}s:32:"db6264aa463a95fc3401cddc9e197487";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:69:"Intel will discontinue desktop motherboards following Haswell release";s:4:"link";s:79:"http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/23/intel-will-discontinue-desktop-motherboards/";s:6:"author";s:12:"Zachary Lutz";s:4:"date";i:1358928600;s:7:"content";s:2187:"<p> <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/23/intel-will-discontinue-desktop-motherboards/"><img alt="" src="http://www.blogcdn.com/www.engadget.com/media/2012/12/intel-1355194310.jpg"></a></p><p> The <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/14/gartner-pc-sales-continue-to-slide-as-tablets-eat-their-lunch/">decline in desktop PC sales</a> is beginning to ripple throughout the industry, as <a href="http://www.engadget.com/tag/intel/">Intel</a> has revealed plans to wind down its desktop motherboard division over the next three years. According to <em>AnandTech</em>, the company will release boards that are based on the <a href="http://www.engadget.com/tag/haswell/">Haswell</a> architecture before completely suspending development. Moving forward, Intel will instead focus its efforts on creating form factor reference designs for the Ultrabook, tablet and desktop markets. Curiously, one product that's currently immune from the announcement is the <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2012/09/14/intels-core-i3-nuc-mini-system-bares-it-all-for-idf-hands-on-v/">Next Unit of Computing</a> (NUC), a miniature barebones system that will see continual development from Intel. While custom PC builders will likely take a moment to reflect upon the news, it's said that the transition is unlikely to affect the company's workforce. Instead, current employees will be absorbed into other divisions within Intel. After all, there's no point in showing talented engineers to the door, even in an age of market shifts.</p><p> [Image credit: <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/huangjiahui/">huangjiahui</a>, <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/huangjiahui/4907798630/">Flickr</a>]</p><p>Filed under: <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/desktops/" rel="tag">Desktops</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/intel/" rel="tag">Intel</a></p><p><strong><a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/23/intel-will-discontinue-desktop-motherboards/#comments">Comments</a></strong></p><p><strong>Source:</strong> <a target="_blank" href="http://www.anandtech.com/show/6685/the-end-of-an-era-intels-desktop-motherboard-business-to-ramp-down-over-next-3-years">AnandTech</a><!--//--></p>";s:9:"feed_link";s:24:"http://www.engadget.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:8:"Engadget";}s:32:"c3b1e96268d0dd0e64e579ee67232a4d";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:70:"The No-Hire Emails That That Incriminate Apple, Google, Adobe and More";s:4:"link";s:119:"http://feeds.gawker.com/~r/gizmodo/full/~3/_71k4vedTgI/the-no+hire-emails-that-that-involve-apple-google-adobe-and-more";s:6:"author";s:15:"Jamie Condliffe";s:4:"date";i:1358928019;s:7:"content";s:2138:"<div> <!-- div style="background-color: #B3B3B3; width: 190px; padding: 1px;"><a title="Click here to read The No-Hire Emails That That Incriminate Apple, Google, Adobe and More" href="http://gizmodo.com/business/" style="background-color:#888888; color:#FFFFFF; font-size:12px;text-align:right; display:block; height:14px; padding:1px 2px; text-decoration:none; text-transform:uppercase; width:156px;"><span style="color: white;" class="hash">#</span><span style="color: white;">business</span></a></div --> <div><a title="Click here to read The No-Hire Emails That That Incriminate Apple, Google, Adobe and More" href="http://gizmodo.com/5978223/the-no+hire-emails-that-that-involve-apple-google-adobe-and-more"> <img height="360" width="640" title="Click here to read The No-Hire Emails That That Incriminate Apple, Google, Adobe and More" alt="Click here to read The No-Hire Emails That That Incriminate Apple, Google, Adobe and More" src="http://img.gawkerassets.com/img/18ccxwqgcldr0png/xlarge.png"></a></div> </div> A court filing has <a href="http://uk.reuters.com/article/2013/01/23/business-us-apple-google-lawsuit-idUKBRE90M04Y20130123">just been made public </a>which sheds light on the "no-hire" gentleman's agreements that have pervaded the tech industry&mdash;and reveals how Steve Jobs threatened litigation to prevent companies from stealing his staff. <a href="http://gizmodo.com/5978223/the-no+hire-emails-that-that-involve-apple-google-adobe-and-more" title="Click here to read more about The No-Hire Emails That That Incriminate Apple, Google, Adobe and More">More&nbsp;&raquo;</a> <br><img width="1" height="1" src="http://gizmodo.feedsportal.com/c/34976/f/647164/s/27cdbe61/mf.gif" border="0"><br><br><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/151884975546/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27cdbe61/a2.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/151884975546/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27cdbe61/a2.img" border="0"></a><img width="1" height="1" src="http://pi.feedsportal.com/r/151884975546/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27cdbe61/a2t.img" border="0"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/gizmodo/full/~4/_71k4vedTgI" height="1" width="1">";s:9:"feed_link";s:19:"http://gizmodo.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:7:"Gizmodo";}s:32:"892e47c3f703002abc3d7727a1ab4719";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:82:"White House unveils National Day of Civic Hacking to solve problems with open data";s:4:"link";s:77:"http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/23/white-house-national-day-of-civic-hacking/";s:6:"author";s:13:"Alexis Santos";s:4:"date";i:1358924520;s:7:"content";s:2188:"<p> <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/23/white-house-national-day-of-civic-hacking/"><img alt="White House unveils National Day of Civic Hacking to solve problems with open data" data-src-height="340" data-src-width="620" src="http://www.blogcdn.com/www.engadget.com/media/2013/01/civichacking.jpg"></a></p><p> Sure, the freshly announced National Day of Civic Hacking may sound like it'll occupy a single square on your calendar, but the White House wants folks to get together on June 1st <em>and</em> 2nd to solve problems with a bit of coding and info from Uncle Sam. Government agencies including the Census Bureau, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/tag/NASA/">NASA</a> and the Department of Labor are set to serve up publicly available data for developers and entrepreneurs to concoct solutions for problems affecting cities, states and the country. In addition to government support, the effort is being organized by outfits including Code for America, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2011/05/23/random-hacks-of-kindness-brings-hackers-together-for-the-greater/">Random Hacks of Kindness</a> and <a href="http://www.engadget.com/tag/EricSchmidt/">Eric Schmidt's</a> Innovation Endeavors. Currently, 27 cities have events scheduled during the weekend in question, but the initiative's coordinators are looking to spawn even more powwows throughout the US. If you'd like to pitch in or submit ideas for challenges participants should tackle, hit the source links below.</p><p>Filed under: <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/misc/" rel="tag">Misc</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/internet/" rel="tag">Internet</a></p><p><strong><a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/23/white-house-national-day-of-civic-hacking/#comments">Comments</a></strong></p><p><strong>Via:</strong> <a href="http://techcrunch.com/2013/01/22/national-day-of-civic-hacking/" target="_blank">TechCrunch</a><!--//--></p><p><strong>Source:</strong> <a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/2013/01/22/roll-your-sleeves-get-involved-and-get-civic-hacking" target="_blank">White House OSTP</a><!--//-->, <a href="http://hackforchange.org/" target="_blank">Hack for Change</a><!--//--></p>";s:9:"feed_link";s:24:"http://www.engadget.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:8:"Engadget";}s:32:"57335e319e3da2e5b8dae7d25ab118ec";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:54:"Sundance 2013: Sundance Un