</div><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/thr/news/~4/x1rg4wJhZEg" height="1" width="1">";s:9:"feed_link";s:33:"http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:18:"Hollywood Reporter";}s:32:"872b4a7a2c2ce6ce0f1c076abf74e4f5";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:66:"DARPA touts progress on Phoenix program to salvage dead satellites";s:4:"link";s:100:"http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/22/darpa-touts-progress-on-phoenix-program-to-salvage-dead-satellit/";s:6:"author";s:15:"Donald Melanson";s:4:"date";i:1358898660;s:7:"content";s:1810:"<p> <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/22/darpa-touts-progress-on-phoenix-program-to-salvage-dead-satellit/"><img alt="DARPA touts progress on Phoenix program to salvage dead satellites" data-src-height="349" data-src-width="620" src="http://www.blogcdn.com/www.engadget.com/media/2013/01/darpa-phoenix-satellite.jpg"></a></p><p> DARPA made some bold promises last summer when it announced its <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2012/06/28/pentagon-starts-phoenix-dead-satellite-trial/">Phoenix program</a> to harvest dead satellites for still-valuable parts, but it didn't have much more than some concept videos to show at the time. It looks like the agency has been making some steady progress since then, though, and has today released a new video showing some of the work it's done up through November of last year. As you can see after the break, that work is all still being doing in the lab, but it covers quite a few of the components that DARPA ultimately hopes to use in space, including robotic arms and gripping mechanisms. Those tests will remain Earth-bound for the next few years, but a demonstration mission is slated for 2016 to see how the system fares on an actual satellite in orbit. </p><p> </p><p>Filed under: <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/science/" rel="tag">Science</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/alt/" rel="tag">Alt</a></p><p><strong><a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/22/darpa-touts-progress-on-phoenix-program-to-salvage-dead-satellit/#comments">Comments</a></strong></p><p><strong>Via:</strong> <a target="_blank" href="http://phys.org/news/2013-01-military-life-dead-satellites.html">PhysOrg</a><!--//--></p><p><strong>Source:</strong> <a target="_blank" href="http://www.darpa.mil/NewsEvents/Releases/2013/01/22a.aspx">DARPA</a><!--//--></p>";s:9:"feed_link";s:24:"http://www.engadget.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:8:"Engadget";}s:32:"1255e05da4c05820fa4295ea789a8ce1";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:92:"Sundance 2013: Paul Rudd on 'Prince Avalanche' and the David Gordon Green Experience (Video)";s:4:"link";s:66:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/thr/news/~3/dIMKonxzxTA/story01.htm";s:6:"author";s:19:"Sophie A. Schillaci";s:4:"date";i:1358898476;s:7:"content";s:2684:"<img src="http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/sites/default/files/2013/01/rudd_a.jpg"><br>The actor and director, along with co-star Emile Hirsch, stopped by THR&rsquo;s video lounge to give their first interview on the film.<p><a href="http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/risky-business/sundance-2013-paul-rudd-prince-414599" target="_blank">read more</a></p><img width="1" height="1" src="http://rss.feedsportal.com/c/34793/f/641578/s/27cbddac/mf.gif" border="0"><div><table border="0"><tr><td valign="middle"><a href="http://share.feedsportal.com/viral/sendEmail.cfm?lang=en&amp;title=Sundance+2013%3A+Paul+Rudd+on+%27Prince+Avalanche%27+and+the+David+Gordon+Green+Experience+%28Video%29&amp;link=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.hollywoodreporter.com%2Frisky-business%2Fsundance-2013-paul-rudd-prince-414599" target="_blank"><img src="http://res3.feedsportal.com/images/emailthis2.gif" border="0"></a></td><td valign="middle"><a href="http://res.feedsportal.com/viral/bookmark.cfm?title=Sundance+2013%3A+Paul+Rudd+on+%27Prince+Avalanche%27+and+the+David+Gordon+Green+Experience+%28Video%29&amp;link=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.hollywoodreporter.com%2Frisky-business%2Fsundance-2013-paul-rudd-prince-414599" target="_blank"><img src="http://res3.feedsportal.com/images/bookmark.