-ever">downloading entire Twitter archives</a> has finally come true, but they pretty much become stale the minute they hit our hard drive. Plus, unless you have access to some sort of webhosting, there's no real way to share your every thought, complaint, and witticism from the past 5 years with the adoring masses. <a href="http://gizmodo.com/5978064/how-to-make-sure-your-twitter-archive-is-always-up-to-date" title="Click here to read more about How to Make Sure Your Twitter Archive Is Always Up to Date">More&nbsp;&raquo;</a> <br><img width="1" height="1" src="http://gizmodo.feedsportal.com/c/34976/f/647164/s/27ca403e/mf.gif" border="0"><br><br><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/151884791082/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27ca403e/kg/342/a2.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/151884791082/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27ca403e/kg/342/a2.img" border="0"></a><img width="1" height="1" src="http://pi.feedsportal.com/r/151884791082/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27ca403e/kg/342/a2t.img" border="0"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/gizmodo/full/~4/-dHshKk9cMA" height="1" width="1">";s:9:"feed_link";s:19:"http://gizmodo.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:7:"Gizmodo";}s:32:"a0b9ede12680115d5f40a918ca669e3d";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:73:"Netflix streaming most dominant on HDTVs, more than double PC and tablets";s:4:"link";s:67:"http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/22/netflix-streaming-usage-hdtv-pc/";s:6:"author";s:11:"Ben Gilbert";s:4:"date";i:1358887140;s:7:"content";s:3248:"<p> <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/22/netflix-streaming-usage-hdtv-pc/"><img alt="Netflix streaming most dominant on HDTVs, more than double PC and tablets" data-src-height="340" data-src-width="620" src="http://www.blogcdn.com/www.engadget.com/media/2013/01/louienetflixinstant620x340pxhedimg.jpg"></a></p><p> As it turns out, the general public -- even us heathens who've <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2012/08/20/editorial-cutting-the-cable-cord-a-la-carte-trend/">cut the cord</a> -- like watching video content on televisions rather than monitors. A stat chart culled from The NPD Group's, "<span>Connected Intelligence Report, Application &amp; Convergence" revealed the latest US-centric news on <a href="http://www.engadget.com/tag/netflix">Netflix Instant</a> usage; it puts HDTV use far above that of more traditional platforms like PCs and laptops. Averaged across age groups, 40 percent of people using Netflix Instant in the US are doing so on HDTVs, while just 14 percent are going through computers (both desktops and laptops). That's not just Smart TVs, but also, "another device connected to the TV" -- so that's <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2012/12/04/sony-playstation-3-netflix-streaming/">game consoles</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/tag/roku">streaming boxes</a>, <em>and</em> software level built-in streaming.</span></p><p> <span>A mere 13 percent are using the service on tablets, and a paltry 8 percent are streaming on smartphones (a stat David Lynch would <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BcNLEwf2pOw">assuredly relish</a>). Unsurprisingly, users are primarily of the younger variety: over 50 percent of 18 to 25-year-olds make up the HDTV statistic, and that group makes up nearly a full quarter of PC folks. Of course, none of this is a huge surprise to anyone that's ever tried comfortably watching anything longer than a few minutes on a 13-inch laptop screen. Check out the full chart just below.</span></p><p> <img alt="Netflix streaming most dominant on HDTVs, more than double PC and tablets" data-src-height="465" data-src-width="620" src="http://www.blogcdn.com/www.engadget.com/media/2013/01/netflixstreaminguse620.jpg"></p><p>Filed under: <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/cellphones/" rel="tag">Cellphones</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/desktops/" rel="tag">Desktops</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/displays/" rel="tag">Displays</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/home-entertainment/" rel="tag">Home Entertainment</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/laptops/" rel="tag">Laptops</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/tablets/" rel="tag">Tablets</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/internet/" rel="tag">Internet</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/software/" rel="tag">Software</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/hd/" rel="tag">HD</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/mobile/" rel="tag">Mobile</a></p><p><strong><a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/22/netflix-streaming-usage-hdtv-pc/#comments">Comments</a></strong></p><p><strong>Source:</strong> <a target="_blank" href="https://www.npdgroupblog.com/netflix-is-not-a-channel-2/">The NPD Group</a><!--//--></p>";s:9:"feed_link";s:24:"http://www.engadget.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:8:"Engadget";}s:32:"e2dc65fd69ae61e7a500b50b55e3042c";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:57:"Study Says It Can Track NFL Brain Injuries with PET Scans";s:4:"link";s:116:"http://feeds.gawker.com/~r/gizmodo/full/~3/VQff-tZ1Qt4/study-confirms-it-can-track-nfl-brain-injuries-with-pet-scans";s:6:"author";s:11:"Kyle Wagner";s:4:"date";i:1358886196;s:7:"content";s:2291:"<div> <!-- div style="background-color: #B3B3B3; width: 190px; padding: 1px;"><a title="Click here to read Study Says It Can Track NFL Brain Injuries with PET Scans" href="http://gizmodo.com/brain-injuries/" style="background-color:#888888; color:#FFFFFF; font-size:12px;text-align:right; display:block; height:14px; padding:1px 2px; text-decoration:none; text-transform:uppercase; width:156px;"><span style="color: white;" class="hash">#</span><span style="color: white;">braininjuries</span></a></div --> <div><a title="Click here to read Study Says It Can Track NFL Brain Injuries with PET Scans" href="http://gizmodo.com/5978097/study-confirms-it-can-track-nfl-brain-injuries-with-pet-scans"> <img height="360" width="640" title="Click here to read Study Says It Can Track NFL Brain Injuries with PET Scans" alt="Click here to read Study Says It Can Track NFL Brain Injuries with PET Scans" src="http://img.gawkerassets.com/img/18cb8b7lnpd9cjpg/xlarge.jpg"></a></div> </div> The NFL needs this. <a href="http://deadspin.com/5920006/can-science-see-inside-an-nfl-players-skull-before-its-too-late">Dr. Gary Small's study on tracking CTE</a>, the central brain disease in former NFL players, has<a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/23/sports/football/study-suggests-pet-scans-may-identify-cte-in-living-patients.html?smid=tw-share&amp;_r=0"> offered proof of its theory</a> in a study published today: It can use PET scans to track the onset of CTE, and maybe save the lives of current and former players. <!-- %JUMP:More &#187;% --> <a href="http://gizmodo.com/5978097/study-confirms-it-can-track-nfl-brain-injuries-with-pet-scans" title="Click here to read more about Study Says It Can Track NFL Brain Injuries with PET Scans">More&nbsp;&raquo;</a> <br><img width="1" height="1" src="http://gizmodo.feedsportal.com/c/34976/f/647164/s/27ca59bd/mf.gif" border="0"><br><br><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/151884705174/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27ca59bd/a2.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/151884705174/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27ca59bd/a2.img" border="0"></a><img width="1" height="1" src="http://pi.feedsportal.com/r/151884705174/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27ca59bd/a2t.img" border="0"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/gizmodo/full/~4/VQff-tZ1Qt4" height="1" width="1">";s:9:"feed_link";s:19:"http://gizmodo.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:7:"Gizmodo";}s:32:"d3f2a708be5ae3db9efe7cdcc132c3e1";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:75:"Who Cares If They're Probably Impractical? These Wooden Knives Are Stunning";s:4:"link";s:128:"http://feeds.gawker.com/~r/gizmodo/full/~3/RdgwU9AL3SM/who-cares-if-theyre-probably-impractical-these-wooden-knives-are-stunning";s:6:"author";s:16:"Andrew Liszewski";s:4:"date";i:1358886000;s:7:"content";s:2266:"<div> <!-- div style="background-color: #B3B3B3; width: 190px; padding: 1px;"><a title="Click here to read Who Cares If They're Probably Impractical? These Wooden Knives Are Stunning" href="http://gizmodo.com/wish-you-were-here/" style="background-color:#888888; color:#FFFFFF; font-size:12px;text-align:right; display:block; height:14px; padding:1px 2px; text-decoration:none; text-transform:uppercase; width:156px;"><span style="color: white;" class="hash">#</span><span style="color: white;">wishyouwerehere</span></a></div --> <div><a title="Click here to read Who Cares If They're Probably Impractical? These Wooden Knives Are Stunning" href="http://gizmodo.com/5978048/who-cares-if-theyre-probably-impractical-these-wooden-knives-are-stunning"> <img height="360" width="640" title="Click here to read Who Cares If They're Probably Impractical? These Wooden Knives Are Stunning" alt="Click here to read Who Cares If They're Probably Impractical? These Wooden Knives Are Stunning" src="http://img.gawkerassets.com/img/18caxp97db7d4jpg/xlarge.jpg"></a></div> </div> There's probably a good reason the master knife makers of the world traditionally choose steel and other metals for their blades, instead of maple. But even if these wooden knives, designed by <a href="http://thefederal.co/Maple-Set">The Federal</a>, aren't as durable or lack the heft of a traditional blade, they'd still make a gorgeous addition to any kitchen, particularly one sporting a butcher block counter. <a href="http://gizmodo.com/5978048/who-cares-if-theyre-probably-impractical-these-wooden-knives-are-stunning" title="Click here to read more about Who Cares If They're Probably Impractical? These Wooden Knives Are Stunning">More&nbsp;&raquo;</a> <br><img width="1" height="1" src="http://gizmodo.feedsportal.com/c/34976/f/647164/s/27ca59b9/mf.gif" border="0"><br><br><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/151884958453/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27ca59b9/a2.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/151884958453/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27ca59b9/a2.img" border="0"></a><img width="1" height="1" src="http://pi.feedsportal.com/r/151884958453/u